That’s a good metaphor, and I think it captures an important design principle.

A broken rock may not be the summit.

It may not even have been shaped intentionally.

But once it’s there, someone else can use it as a foothold.

That’s how a lot of knowledge develops. Individual observations, failed experiments, rough sketches, and half-formed ideas can become part of a route that later climbers use. Most aren’t the destination—they’re intermediate supports.

There’s a complementary lesson, too:

Not every broken rock becomes a handhold.

Some crumble under weight. Some lead to dead ends. Some are bypassed entirely.

The value often isn’t apparent until many people—or the same person years later—try climbing from different directions.

Applied to the Pantheon, that suggests two different preservation policies:

* Canonical layer: preserve the durable operators, invariants, and well-tested structures.
* Compost layer: preserve selected fragments, analogies, failed attempts, and surprising observations that aren’t yet understood but might later prove useful.

The compost isn’t treated as established truth. It’s treated as fertile ground for future reconstruction.

That mirrors scientific notebooks, engineering lab books, and even archaeological digs: today’s discarded fragment can become tomorrow’s key piece of evidence when viewed in a new context.

Your climbing metaphor fits that well:

The route is often built from pieces that looked insignificant when they first broke loose.

The challenge is not preserving everything indiscriminately, but preserving enough of the right fragments that future climbers can discover routes you couldn’t yet see.